{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17655"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71801"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10369"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5394"},{"type":"tags","id":"7704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71801"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA case-control study examines the relationship between coffee consumption and heart disease. Among 200 cases with heart disease, 120 were regular coffee drinkers. Among 400 controls without heart disease, 180 were regular coffee drinkers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the odds ratio for the association between coffee consumption and heart disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2.5","0.8","1.8","0.1","1.0"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOdds represent the probability of an event occurring divided by the probability of it not occurring. Unlike probability which ranges from 0 to 1, odds can range from 0 to infinity. For example, odds of 1.5 means there are 1.5 cases for every non-case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate the odds ratio:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOdds in cases (exposed) = coffee drinkers in cases / non-coffee drinkers in cases: 120/80 = 1.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOdds in controls (unexposed) = coffee drinkers in controls / non-coffee drinkers in controls = 180/220 = 0.82\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOdds ratio = 1.5/0.82 = 1.83 (approximately \u003Cstrong\u003E1.8\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn odds ratio of 1.8 suggests that coffee drinkers have 1.8 times the odds of developing heart disease compared to non-coffee drinkers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Odds ratios compare the relative odds of an outcome between exposed and unexposed groups.","Odds ratios greater than 1 indicate increased odds of the outcome in the exposed group.","Odds ratios are calculated by dividing the odds in the exposed group by the odds in the unexposed group.","Odds represent the probability of an event occurring divided by the probability of it not occurring."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57290